\block{The everlasting discussion\ldots}{
{\large\ldots on programmable calculators and computer usage during exams}
\begin{itemize}
\item The issue is not about the device being programmable but
  \okis{who is in control}.
\item Solution: take away control from the student for the duration of
  the exam session:
  \begin{itemize}
  \item Disallow network access (to e.g. \url{n@tschool}, DropBox, Google~drive, outlook/mail etc.
  \item Disallow wireless (bluetooth to e.g. smart phone) all
    together.
  \item Disallow access to installed (uncontrolled) local storage. (Students data).
  \end{itemize}
\item Only allow the programs on the managed storage.

\end{itemize}
}

  \block{Current features of the SEBI-Sandbox.}{
    \begin{itemize}
    \item Runs on mainstream laptops, including Apple Mac.
    \item Linux based. Free, without any license issues.
    \item No wireless communication whatsoever (reason \alert{security!}).
    \item Boot to graphical desktop without login.
    \item Network access using functional Fontys account.
    \item Developer tools: Java SDK and Netbeans or Bluej.
    \item Any programming language supported in Linux (try to name one that
      is not\ldots).
    \item JEE container for java enterprise applications.
    \item Version control client. GUI and CLI versions.
    \item Web browsers: Firefox and Google-Chrome.
    \item Postgresql database server with installed exam sample
      database.
    \item Database GUI-client to database server.
    \item Libreoffice suite as alternative to MS-Office apps like
      MS-Access and MS-Excel.
    \item Libreoffice connected to the postgresql database.
    \item Xtuple ERP application including installed (postgresql) exam
      sample database.
    \item Possibility to use non-US keyboards.
    \item Potentially everything that is available  under Linux.
    \item All on a mainstream USB-stick.\\
